## **TL-DR:** Three variations of solution

![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/a5d97667-f9a5-4974-8339-f0528f10ce5f_1660699065.9906268.png)

```
var uniqueMorseRepresentations = function(words) {
	const morseCode = { a: ".-", b: "-...", c: "-.-.", d: "-..", e: ".", f: "..-.", g: "--.", h: "....", i: "..", j: ".---", k: "-.-", l: ".-..", m: "--", n: "-.", o: "---", p: ".--.", q: "--.-", r: ".-.", s: "...", t: "-", u: "..-", v: "...-", w: ".--", x: "-..-", y: "-.--", z: "--.." }
    const morseRepresentation = word => word.split('').map(c => morseCode[c]).join('');

    return new Set(words.map(morseRepresentation)).size;
};
```

---

## **First** acceptance

At beginning, I was using a `reduce()` function to insert each transformation into the set at time:

```
var uniqueMorseRepresentations = function(words) {
    return words.reduce((set, w) => set.add(transform(w)), new Set()).size;

    function transform(word) {
        const morse = [".-","-...","-.-.","-..",".","..-.","--.","....","..",".---","-.-",".-..","--","-.","---",".--.","--.-",".-.","...","-","..-","...-",".--","-..-","-.--","--.."]
        return word.split('').map(c => morse[c.charCodeAt() - 'a'.charCodeAt()]).join('');
    }
};
```

---

## **Cleaner way** to use `Set()`

As the [Set() constructor](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Global_Objects/Set/Set/) accepts any [iterable object](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Iteration_protocols#the_iterable_protocol) as argument, we can achieve the same result in a better way.

Even it would be possible to have a solution in one single line - as we can see at [@acupoftee's great one line solution](https://leetcode.com/problems/unique-morse-code-words/discuss/329303/JavaScript-One-Line-Solution-w-Explanation-(52-ms-beats-94)) - keeping the `transform(word)` function helps to have a lot cleaner solution:

```
var uniqueMorseRepresentations = function(words) {
    const morse = [".-","-...","-.-.","-..",".","..-.","--.","....","..",".---","-.-",".-..","--","-.","---",".--.","--.-",".-.","...","-","..-","...-",".--","-..-","-.--","--.."]

    return new Set(words.map(transformWord)).size;

    function transformWord (word) {
        return word.split('').map(c => morse[c.charCodeAt() - 'a'.charCodeAt()]).join('');
    }
};
```

![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/fed24540-1ab1-4be6-b9e5-bb9e665cd5ce_1660697627.3583236.png)

---

## **Best approach** using *hash table* to keep values

Finally, a last improvement that can be made is to use an *hash table* instead of using the *Array* structure given at problem statement.

It will not just make it easier to read and simpler to code, but also will be a lot more efficient, as it will not be necessary any more to make the *maths* and function calls involving ASCII code to find the correct index for morse representations: 

```
var uniqueMorseRepresentations = function(words) {
	const morse = { a: ".-", b: "-...", c: "-.-.", d: "-..", e: ".", f: "..-.", g: "--.", h: "....", i: "..", j: ".---", k: "-.-", l: ".-..", m: "--", n: "-.", o: "---", p: ".--.", q: "--.-", r: ".-.", s: "...", t: "-", u: "..-", v: "...-", w: ".--", x: "-..-", y: "-.--", z: "--.." }
    const transformWord = word => word.split('').map(c => morse[c]).join('');

    return new Set(words.map(transformWord)).size;
};
```

