## if u find it helpful , please give it a upvote

### Approach
1) creating a vector of codes.
2) convert a word to code by traversing each letter of a word and getting the code for the letter from vector 
3) concatinating the code into a string 
4) the string containing transformation of a word is inserted into a set
5) repeating for all words
6) set contains unique values , so will contain only unique tranformations
7) returning set size as the number of different transformations.

### C++ solution
```
class Solution {
public:
    int uniqueMorseRepresentations(vector<string>& words) {
        vector<string> v = {".-","-...","-.-.","-..",".","..-.","--.","....","..",".---","-.-",".-..","--","-.","---",".--.","--.-",".-.","...","-","..-","...-",".--","-..-","-.--","--.."};
        set<string> set;
        for(int i=0;i<words.size();i++){
            string temp = "";
            for(int j=0;j<words[i].size();j++){
                temp+=v[words[i][j]-'a'];
            }
            set.insert(temp);
            temp.clear();
        }
        return set.size();
    }
};
```

