# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
```text[left: start]``` means the first left chunk and ```text[end: right]``` means the second right chunk. If they are equal, find the next chunks i.e. ```text[start: start + 1]``` and ```text[end - 1: end]```. If not, increase the size of both the chunks by 1. Keep storing the results of all the sub-problems.

# Complexity
- Time complexity: $$O(n)$$
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: $$O(n)$$
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution:
    def longestDecomposition(self, text: str) -> int:
        self.res, sz = 0, len(text)

        @cache
        def dp(left: int, start: int, end: int, right: int) -> int:
            if left == start == end == right:
                return 1
            if start >= end:
                return 0
            if text[left: start + 1] == text[end: right + 1]:
                return dp(start + 1, start + 1, end - 1, end - 1) + 2
            chunk = dp(left, start + 1, end - 1, right)
            return chunk if chunk > 0 else 1

        return dp(0, 0, sz - 1, sz - 1)
