solutions.content:
Start with an example: "abcabc"
We want to start from either side and construct 2 strings simultaneously: ```left``` & ```right```
```left``` is the first ```lo``` characters of ```text```, 
```right``` is the last ```hi``` characters of ```text``` 

If ```left == reverse(right)```, we have found a palindromic decompostion, hence we add 2 to the ```count```, and reset ```left``` and ```right```
We shrink our two pointers (```lo++``` and ```hi--```)


Corner case: if there's no palindromic decomposition, ```count=1```
Or if only one character left at the end (```lo == hi```), increment ```count``` by 1


I guess the tricky part was to figure out the "greedy-ness" of the solution. Since we want to maximize the number of palindromic decompositions, as soon as we come across a palindromic decomposition, we create a split. 

We can prove this using contradiction:
Consider the ```subtext_i``` and suffix ```subtext_k-i+1``` of ```text```. 
And let's say we have already found the "max" palindromic decomposition by breaking ```text``` into ```k``` substrings. 

But if ```subtext_i[0:x] == (subtext_k-i+1[end-x:end] = reverse(subtext_k-i+1)[0:x]``` for any ```0 < x < len(subtext_i)```, then we can break down ```subtext_i``` & ```subtext_k-i+1``` into 2 pairs: ```subtext_i[0:x] & subtext_k-i+1[end-x:end]``` & ```subtext_i[x:end] & subtext_k-i+1[0:x]```.
Hence resulting in ```k+2``` decompositions rather than ```k``` which is a contradiction.


Hope that makes it clear. 

```
class Solution {
public:
    int longestDecomposition(string text) {
        string left, right;
        int n = text.size();
        int lo = 0, hi = n-1;
        int count = 0;

        while (lo < hi) {
            left.push_back(text[lo++]);
            right.push_back(text[hi--]);
            reverse(right.begin(), right.end());
            if (left == right) {
                count += 2;
                left = "";
                right = "";
            }
            else {
                reverse(right.begin(), right.end());
            }
        }

        if (!left.empty() || !right.empty() || lo == hi) ++count;
        return count;
    }
};
```

